Florian was born in Romania, just two hours away from the Black Sea.

His parents gave him away right after his birth, so he grew up in a orphanage. There he not only experienced physical violence, but was repeatedly sexually abused by a teacher. 
In 2009 Florian left Romania to start over in Germany. But life didn't get much better, because he didn't speak any German and didn't know anyone, he ended up sleeping in the streets and surviving on the little money he made as a sex worker. 
Although life is was harsh for Florian, he didn't loose his happiness. Today he works as a cleaner at a sex club. With @steveemeyer he shared his life story and explained how to properly clean after a fisting party for @vice_de // thanks you @sasarndm for asking me to take his portraits.

That one time I took an American, an Argentinan and an Vietnamese to the Saxony alps. Slept open air in a forest, had breakfast at the water, used Roibusch vanilla tea instead of tobacco to smoke, got on the top of things, made a bon fire at some local couchsurfing hippies garden, lost my wallet, found my wallet and had a Martin Parr moment at the unesco heritage Bastei Bridge. Two nights felt like two weeks. 
I miss you summer, please come back soon.

„Regardless of how you feel about me, I chose to be myself and this makes me a happy human.” - Biggie runs an organization that gives a safe hangout space for lesbians in Kampala/Uganda. Her organization not only gives women a safe place to be openly gay, but also provide those women that are still married to their husbands with lube, which is a life savior.The present life in Uganda is especially tough for homosexual women, also the fear of being an victim of "corrective rape" lures around every corner. It's better when people don't know where you liv, she tells me. Although she might be limited in her freedom of movement since she's publicly out of the closet, the one thing that no man can strip away from Biggie is her power to fight for her rights and the hope that with younger generation in Uganda comes a change of societies mindset. It's only a question of time. //From my project Rainbow pride
. . . .

Systemabsturz is a brand new band project of Sofia and Victor connected to Digitale Freiheit, a political student movement that tries to build bridges between the world of tech nerds and regular people that don't study math. Digitale Freiheit does creative street protests, organizes parties, raises awareness about data rights and want you to you read the terms and conditions before you sign up on platforms. 
While the lyrics of Systemabsturz mostly try to make tech vocabulary seem cool, they are also extremely easy to sing along. The sound of Systemabsturz mixes electronic beats with synth pop punk and is obviously influenced by Neue Deutsche Welle. 
Today Systemabsturz released their first EP on Spotify, Apple Music, Bandcamp, Soundcloud and more. You can also download it from netzpolitik.org, a German blog covering tech and data security topics. 
I am more than stoked that I can finally share the DIY music video we winged with a bunch of friends and housemates in three intense nights in a corner of our living room. Leave love in the comment section and share it with your friends if you also think this song has potential to be a hit. 🥂

“After the war, the country was very poor, but the population cared for the wounds and pains of our veterans. We were very respected when we returned to our homes, we were greeted by the loving arms of our families and communities. In 1990, I was invited by the American television station CBS to the US to give lectures to US veterans. At first, it was difficult for me to meet US veterans and tell them my story. But later I heard from them that my experiences were very similar to theirs. Friends who died and who they had to bury them during the ongoing operation. For the first time, we met as humans." --Nguyen Ngoc Hung (70) fought as a North Vietnamese soldier for six years and was one of the first North Vietnamese to visit the United States in 1999.

I recently got interviewed by the German @szmagazin about the veterans and linked it in my bio✌️
.
.

I was 23 years old and my one true love was backpacking. The only thing that kept me sane in an insane world was reducing my needs to fit in an 15l backpack and be a nobody. Start over in every place with no history attached. From brief conversations to deep connections. When leaving my issues and problems at home, Life felt more pure, more intense, more colorful.

I wanted to do my bachelor thesis on backpacking culture and a wonderful community I came across a year before in Central America. Interesting people from all over, guys in girls dresses, puppies, parrots, loud techno music and dancing on tables. Age didn't matter, there was no need  to be an adult in this place.

I befriended the people living here. Became one of them. What seemed like living in paradise turned quickly into realizing that I was trapped in a dejavu of people coming and going. Running away from problems and breaking down.

Three months of flying high and falling deep. I felt like I failed my bachelor thesis, made a book about failing and losing my mind in paradise instead. My teacher hated it and I felt like I traumatized myself for no reason. It took me a very long time to gain my interest in meeting new people again.

What seemed like failure became success , when @vice asked me for an interview. Not much later I got 4000 followers over night. It turned out to be one of the most read articles of 2016 and I got many requests for features. I was happy and confused at the same time. Another feeling of devastation hit me, when got informed that my story was used in the country itself and made a huge scandal. After managing getting out of a lot of trouble, I didn't wanted to have something to do with this story for a very long time. Nowadays I wish I already would have been professional enough to take legal action against local media fucking with my copyright and protect the place better. (more text in comments)

With the days getting colder it feels like 2019 is almost over. This year was already pretty crazy, I never thought I would ever met the inspiring members of @seawatchcrew - I followed and admired their work already for many years. When they welcomed me on boat earlier this year, I spent days watching videos of rescues on YouTube to prepare myself for some pretty horrible stuff. But everything came different, we were seized in Marseille and I learned how to paint a mast and derost the steering compartment. It was depressing to be seized with a very capable crew but It was still good times, I made new friends, enjoyed silly jokes and discovered that Marseille is not the worst place to be. Instead of documenting rescues I did a little photography project that gave an insight into the  personal opinions of the crew.

The Good:
After I left, they sued the government, won the case, went on mission. Broke some laws,  beat salvini and saved some lives.

The Bad:
Again, they are seized since 90 days.

I want to stay positive, there is so much happening in current politics and people are trying to have impact and unfuck the world. yes, I truly hope this shit is real, good things come out and maybe I get a chance to go out on mission a  next year. .
.
.
.
#seawatch #searescueisnotacrime #safepassage #searescue #boats #refugeeswelcome #unfucktheworld

"I am deeply invested in investigating tenderness, my own and others. I see how the way society has been structured demands a numbness, a hardening around the soul, to protect yourself from the tiny and large hurts that lay looming ahead. I want to create communities where you are never made to feel that you are too much or not enough. I want to create space for the vulnerability we all possess to come home to our bodies and to feel safe again. I find it so beautiful how many people find home in queerness and that it looks differently for every person. I'm grateful for our diversity and I know it is our strength." Riley (24) is non binary, uses They/Them pronouns. In Berlin I had the pleasure to get weird and photograph them for my rainbow pride project 🌈
